Chapter:
Example Implementations
    This chapter contains implementation examples of some methods from the
    SimplicialSurface-package. Every section discusses a method in the
    following way:


Short explanation of the method

Presentation of the code

Development of the code



VertexCounter
        The method VertexCounter ()
        counts the edge--degrees of all vertices and collects those in a list:
        The entry at position
        pos counts the number of vertices with exactly pos 
        incident edges.

        This could be implemented like this:

gap> VertexCounter_custom := function( complex )
>     local edgeDegrees, colDegrees, count, pair;
>
>     edgeDegrees := List( EdgesOfVertices(complex), Size );
>     colDegrees := Collected( Compacted( edgeDegrees ) );
>
>     count := [];
>     for pair in colDegrees do
>         count[pair[1]] := pair[2];
>     od;
> 
>     return count;
> end;;

        We illustrate this on the example of a pyramid with square base.

            \input{Image_SquarePyramid.tex}


gap> pyr := PolygonalSurfaceByVerticesInFaces( 
>            [ [3,4,5,6], [1,3,4], [1,4,5], [1,5,6], [1,6,3] ]);;
gap> VertexCounter( pyr );
[ , , 4, 1 ]
gap> VertexCounter_custom( pyr );
[ , , 4, 1 ]

        How do we arrive at this code? 

        First of all we have to find the relevant information. We want to
        count how many edges are incident to a vertex. Therefore we use
        the method EdgesOfVertices that gives us exactly this 
        information. Since we only want to know the number of edges,
        we apply the method Size to every component.

gap> edgeDegrees := List( EdgesOfVertices(pyr), Size );
[ 4, , 3, 3, 3, 3 ]

        Now we need to count how often each entry appears. This can be done
        by a loop but we will use the &GAP;-function Collected instead.
        Unfortunately it only works for lists without holes:

gap> Collected( edgeDegrees );
Error, List Element: <list>[2] must have an assigned value

        If we want to program with this package, we have to expect
        holes. In this case it is sufficient to remove all holes
        with the  &GAP;-function Compacted.

gap> Compacted( edgeDegrees );
[ 4, 3, 3, 3, 3 ]
gap> colDegrees := Collected( Compacted( edgeDegrees ) );
[ [ 3, 4 ], [ 4, 1 ] ]

        From this list we can read of the result: There are four vertices
        with edge degree 3 and one vertex of edge degree 4. To translate it
        into the form of a list, we can use a for-loop.

gap>  count := [];;
gap>  for pair in colDegrees do
>         count[pair[1]] := pair[2];
>     od;
gap>  count;
[ , , 4, 1 ]
